<h2>How to Get Your Local Business Recommended by ChatGPT</h2>
<p>ChatGPT now has over 800 million weekly active users. Many of them ask it for local business recommendations instead of searching Google.</p>
<p>If your business does not show up in those answers, you are losing customers to competitors who do.</p>
<p>The local business ChatGPT recommendation problem is new. Most business owners do not know ChatGPT pulls from specific data sources. They do not know which platforms matter. And they do not know that AI referral traffic converts at 4.4x the rate of traditional search traffic.</p>
<p>We publish 3,500+ blog posts across 70+ industries. We track how AI search engines source, rank, and cite local businesses every day. This guide is built on that data.</p>
<p>Here is what you will learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>How ChatGPT actually sources local business recommendations</li>
<li>The 8 steps to make your business visible to AI search</li>
<li>Which platforms feed ChatGPT directly (some will surprise you)</li>
<li>How to monitor whether ChatGPT recommends your business</li>
</ul>
<p>No fluff. No theory. Just the exact steps that get local businesses cited by AI.</p>
<h2>How ChatGPT Sources Local Business Recommendations</h2>
<p>ChatGPT does not search the internet the same way Google does. Understanding where it pulls data is the first step to showing up in its answers.</p>
<p>ChatGPT uses 3 primary sources for local business information:</p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Source</th>
<th>What It Provides</th>
<th>Priority</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Bing Search API</td>
<td>Real-time web results, business listings</td>
<td>High</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Foursquare</td>
<td>Business name, address, category, ratings</td>
<td>High</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Training Data</td>
<td>Historical web content, reviews, mentions</td>
<td>Medium</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p><a href="https://www.localfalcon.com/blog/chatgpt-local-search-data-sources-where-does-business-info-come-from">A study from Local Falcon</a> found that 60% to 70% of local businesses ChatGPT shows come directly from Foursquare data. ChatGPT also relies on Bing's search API for 92% of its real-time web searches.</p>
<p>This means your traditional Google-first SEO strategy leaves major gaps. You need to be visible on the platforms ChatGPT actually reads.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="How ChatGPT sources local business data" src="/images/blog/chatgpt-local-business-data-sources.webp" /></p>
<p>ChatGPT evaluates 5 signals before recommending a business:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Authoritative list mentions</strong> on high-ranking websites</li>
<li><strong>Awards and accreditations</strong> from recognized organizations</li>
<li><strong>Online reviews</strong> across platforms like Google, Yelp, and Trustpilot</li>
<li><strong>Customer usage data</strong> showing real adoption and engagement</li>
<li><strong>Social sentiment</strong> from Reddit, X, and news coverage</li>
</ol>
<p>Businesses with review scores below 70% positive are far less likely to get recommended. The bar is not perfection. It is consistent quality across multiple platforms.</p>
<p>Now let us walk through each step.</p>
<h2>Step 1: Claim and Optimize Your Google Business Profile</h2>
<p>Your Google Business Profile remains the single most important local listing on the internet. It feeds AI tools that pull from Google's data ecosystem. And it is the foundation every other optimization builds on.</p>
<p><strong>Specifically:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Claim your profile at <a href="https://business.google.com">business.google.com</a> if you have not already</li>
<li>[ ] Complete every field: name, address, phone, website, hours, service area</li>
<li>[ ] Select the most specific primary category for your business</li>
<li>[ ] Add 3 to 5 secondary categories that describe your services</li>
<li>[ ] Upload at least 10 high-quality photos (exterior, interior, team, work)</li>
<li>[ ] Write a business description with your primary services and location</li>
<li>[ ] Add all services and products with descriptions</li>
</ul>
<p>A <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">complete GBP</a> sends strong signals to both Google and the AI systems that pull from Google's index. ChatGPT cross-references multiple data points. The more complete your profile, the more confident the AI is in recommending you.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> ChatGPT mirrors many of the top Google results. If your GBP is incomplete, you rank lower in Google. That means you also rank lower in ChatGPT's data pool.</p>
<p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> <a href="/blog/gbp-categories-guide/">Choose your GBP categories carefully</a>. The primary category carries the most weight. A plumber who lists "Plumber" as the primary category ranks better than one who lists "Home Improvement."</p>
<p>Post regularly to your GBP. Businesses that publish <a href="/blog/gbp-posting-frequency/">GBP posts consistently</a> signal active engagement. AI systems interpret freshness as reliability.</p>
<h2>Step 2: Create and Optimize Your Bing Places Listing</h2>
<p>This is the step most local businesses skip. It is also the most impactful for ChatGPT visibility.</p>
<p>ChatGPT uses the Bing Search API for 92% of its real-time web searches. Bing Places is the local business directory that feeds Bing's search results. If your business is not on Bing Places, ChatGPT may never see you.</p>
<p><strong>Specifically:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Go to <a href="https://www.bingplaces.com">bingplaces.com</a> and claim your listing</li>
<li>[ ] Import your Google Business Profile data to save time</li>
<li>[ ] Verify your business via phone, email, or postcard</li>
<li>[ ] Add photos, business hours, and a detailed description</li>
<li>[ ] Include all service categories and areas served</li>
<li>[ ] Add your website URL with proper tracking parameters</li>
</ul>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/bing-places-guide/">Bing Places listing</a> should mirror your Google Business Profile exactly. Same name. Same address. Same phone number. Same categories. AI models cross-reference data across platforms. Inconsistencies reduce trust.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> Bing Places is ChatGPT's primary source for local business data. Skipping this step is like ignoring Google for traditional SEO.</p>
<p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Bing Places allows you to import your GBP data directly. The entire setup takes under 15 minutes. There is no excuse to skip it.</p>
