<h2>Step 4: Earn Reviews on Platforms AI Models Trust</h2>
<p>Reviews are the most powerful signal that determines whether AI tools recommend your business. <a href="https://firstpagesage.com/seo-blog/chatgpt-optimization-guide/">First Page Sage research</a> found that businesses with review scores below 70% positive are far less likely to appear in ChatGPT answers.</p>
<p>Volume matters. Quality matters more. But platform diversity matters most.</p>
<p><strong>The review platforms that influence ChatGPT:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Google Reviews</strong>. Highest volume, strongest overall signal</li>
<li><strong>Yelp</strong>. Heavy weight in ChatGPT training data</li>
<li><strong>Trustpilot</strong>. Common in B2B and service recommendations</li>
<li><strong>BBB</strong>. Trust and accreditation signal</li>
<li><strong>Industry platforms</strong>. G2, Clutch, Avvo, Healthgrades (depends on your industry)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Specifically:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Build a system to <a href="/blog/ask-customers-for-reviews/">ask every customer for a review</a></li>
<li>[ ] Focus on Google first, then Yelp and industry platforms</li>
<li>[ ] Respond to every review within 24 to 48 hours</li>
<li>[ ] Address negative reviews professionally and specifically</li>
<li>[ ] Aim for 70% or higher positive sentiment across all platforms</li>
</ul>
<p>Do not chase only star ratings. ChatGPT reads review text. A 4.2 star business with 200 detailed reviews outperforms a 4.8 star business with 12 generic ones.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> AI models use review sentiment, volume, and recency to determine recommendation confidence. Thin review profiles equal low confidence. Low confidence means no recommendation.</p>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/review-management-guide/">review management system</a> should treat AI visibility as a core KPI. Not just Google rankings.</p>
